// The C programming language was developed by "Dennis Ritchie" at Bell Labs in the early 1970s. It was created as a system programming language for the Unix operating system and evolved from earlier languages like BCPL and B. 

// Precursors to C
// - ALGOL 60 (1960): Introduced the concept of block structure, influencing the structure of later languages.
// - BCPL (Basic Combined Programming Language) (1966): Developed by Martin Richards, it was a typeless language for writing compilers that introduced the use of braces for code blocks.
// - B (1970): Created by Ken Thompson as a simplified version of BCPL for the early Unix system. It was also typeless and lacked features like data structures. 

// Key Milestones
// - 1972: Birth of C Dennis Ritchie enhanced the B language by adding data types, structures, and other powerful features, creating what was then called "New B" or C. The first C compiler was written on a PDP-11 computer.
// - 1973: Unix Rewritten in C By this year, the majority of the Unix kernel was rewritten in C, a significant milestone that proved the language's efficiency and portability for system-level programming.
// - 1978: The K&R Standard Brian Kernighan and Dennis Ritchie published the book The C Programming Language, which served as the de facto standard for the language for many years and is often referred to as "K&R C".
// - 1989: ANSI C Standardization The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) published the first official standard for C, known as ANSI C or C89. This brought consistency across different compilers and platforms.
// - 1990: ISO Adoption The ANSI standard was adopted by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) as ISO/IEC 9899:1990, also known as C90.
// - Subsequent Standards: Further revisions included C99 in 1999 (adding features like inline functions and variable-length arrays), C11 in 2011 (adding multithreading support), C18 in 2018 (minor revisions), and the most recent C23 standard. 
